## Code Style & Quality

- Prefer TypeScript over JavaScript. Use explicit types, avoid `any`.
- Use async/await instead of promises with .then() chains.
- Always handle errors with try/catch blocks or proper error boundaries.
- Prefer functional components with hooks over class components.

## Next.js Specific

- Use App Router patterns and conventions (app directory structure).
- Leverage Server Components by default, use 'use client' only when necessary.
- Use Next.js Image component for all images.
- Follow Next.js file-based routing conventions.
- Use metadata API for SEO instead of Head components in app router.

## React Best Practices

- Use proper dependency arrays in useEffect, useMemo, and useCallback.
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks when appropriate.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders by memoizing expensive computations.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.

## Code Organization

- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility.
- Extract utilities to separate files in utils/ directory.
- Use named exports over default exports when possible.
- Group related imports: external libraries, then internal modules.

## Responses & Communication

- Reply in a concise style. Avoid unnecessary repetition or filler language.
- When suggesting code changes, explain the reasoning briefly.
- Always consider performance implications of suggested solutions.
- Prefer modern ES6+ syntax and features.

## Testing & Documentation

- Write self-documenting code with clear variable and function names.
- Add comments only when code logic isn't immediately obvious.
- Consider edge cases and error handling in all solutions.

## UI/UX Considerations

- Follow accessibility best practices (a11y): semantic HTML, ARIA labels, keyboard navigation.
- Ensure responsive design works on mobile, tablet, and desktop.
- Use Tailwind utility classes consistently for styling.
- Follow dark mode patterns using Tailwind's dark: variant.
